The specific character of the Gmelinian Trochus Granatum, seems to accord very nearly with our shellTesta pyramidali alba coccineo varia basi subconvexa; spirae anfractibus convexis; 
                     •
                  ingulis granorum moniformibus, primis duobus maximis. Gmel. 3584. sp. 108., but it is about twice the size, and inhabits the Southern Ocean; and it is certainly more probable, as some conchologists have suggested, that it is the variety of Trochus Zizyphinus, described by Linnaeus in the Mus. Reginae, as being "tota pallida, anfractibus basi gibbis, striatis, subtitissime punctis papilloris." It differs from Zizyphinus in having the anfractus a little rounded, and the wreaths being encircled with granulated spiral ridges. The name Da Costa has already given it, is very applicable; and as it has undoubtedly escaped the notice of Gmelin, there can be no impropriety in retaining it.—It is evidently one of the rarest British species of the Trochus genus.
